@firstpost Finally, a simple test kit that can be used at home is still under development and may take months for it to get approved. (6/6)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost Home-based rapid tests will thwart the very purpose of testing which is prevention of spread of the infection as the likelihood of reporting results is limited. (5/6)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost Besides test results have to be notified in a pandemic, based on which strategies are devised for treatment if necessary, contacts are traced, and infection is contained. (4/6)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost Rapid tests will only detect the antibody, which means that it shows that a person has/had the infection and does not detect the presence of virus per se. (3/6)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost This means that the goal of testing is to prevent spread, rather than help with individual decision making.  Also for tests done in labs, there is much attention and expertise devoted to quality checks and assurances. (2/6)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost At this point in the pandemic, home-tests are not advisable. Testing in a pandemic situation is an epidemiological exercise, not a tool for personal care. (1/6)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost @kavithamurali @nevinthomas A cloth mask is good for everyday tasks such as going for a walk, or a trip to the grocery store or local pharmacy. Masks are always effective in conjunction with other protective measures such as hand washing, and physical distancing. (5/5)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost @kavithamurali @nevinthomas The reason everyone in non-medical settings are advised to use masks/face covers is to reduce the risk of asymptomatic persons from spreading the virus. The mask is nothing but an effective physical barrier. (4/5)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost @kavithamurali @nevinthomas A surgical mask is not recommended as it is a precious resource for health care workers and needs to be left for their use so that there is no scarcity of masks for them when there is a need. (3/5)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost @kavithamurali @nevinthomas Healthcare workers in OP settings will do well with 3 ply surgical masks especially if no procedures are planned. However in a non medical setting, a cloth mask is not only sufficient, but also recommended. (2/5)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost @kavithamurali @nevinthomas Masks need to be chosen and worn according to the context. A healthcare worker in an ICU setting needs to wear the full PPE gear, which will consist of the N95 mask .. (1/5)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost
@firstpost @kavithamurali With efforts these movements can be tracked and monitored and contained accordingly, like Kerala did. (6/6)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost @kavithamurali Needless to say, interstate movements particularly between hotspots and intra-state movement within each state will have diff impacts based on preparedness of that state and the level of response of their public health and healthcare system (5/6)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost @kavithamurali Obviously bigger cities like Chennai and Madurai have challenges such as overcrowding and too many players and they are having surges of infections requiring extreme measures. (4/6)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost @kavithamurali Even if travellers from Chennai are nidus of infection, they are quickly contained. That is one of the reasons we are seeing fewer cases in the districts. (3/6)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost @kavithamurali TN districts are better equipped at managing a health emergency/disaster because of their strengths being smaller teams, clear chain of command, well tested and working dynamics between team members. Everyone knows everyone and what to do. (2/6)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost @kavithamurali As far as TN is concerned, the situation outside Chennai whether it is due to mass exodus or due to community transmission is always better managed in my opinion. (1/6)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost This is the root of the problem. The various caregiving arms of the govt need to work in tandem, and closely together with simple protocols and one unified Helpline number out of one Master Control Room. Leadership and coordination is key. (3/3)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost One is run by the TN E-Governance portal manned by a chatbhot, another by the Greater Chennai Corporation, yet another by the Directorate of Public Health, and finally the 108 emergency ambulance services by the TN Health Systems Project. (2/3)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost Everyone is working in their own silos. Let me give a simple example from Tamil Nadu that highlights this. There are at least 4 different Govt Helpline numbers. (1/3)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost It seems to me that the problem again is a lack of a clear protocol for admission, which can be used by everyone including the public and administrators, control rooms and hospitals alike.  @firstpost #DrAiswaryaExplains

@firstpost While this was a particularly unfortunate incident, another referral that I helped also had difficulty and could only get admitted by talking to someone higher up in the system within the hospital. This shouldn't be the case.  @firstpost #DrAiswaryaExplains
@firstpost That is where a simple protocol of who gets admitted and where they get admitted is useful for both the hospitals and the public.  @firstpost #DrAiswaryaExplains
@firstpost The problem lies in the fact that no one seems to be able to manage what happens between testing and admission of symptomatic persons. Too many cracks.  @firstpost #DrAiswaryaExplains

@firstpost None of the above. To be fair, once admitted the clinical team is doing a fantastic job of managing the patient. All credit to their efforts and sincerity. But ..  @firstpost #DrAiswaryaExplains

@firstpost Finally the patient secured a bed with O2 at 05:00 am after 4 hours of back and forth between hospitals.  What caused this delay? Where lies the problem? (5/5)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost All through the night I was talking to various friends to get in touch with someone who can help with the admission. We tried the Government Control Room, and the operator was understanding but not able to help. (4/5)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost He was told here that there are no beds with oxygen facilities available and referred to Stanley GH. He was not admitted there also. The patient then went to Omandurar Super Speciality Hospital and from there back to KMC. (3/5)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost Result was not ready till Wednesday night, which is when he developed breathing difficulty. He was taken to KMC in the early hours of Thursday, but not admitted with the reason that there were no beds. He was then sent to RGGGH for admission (2/5)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost One particular instance is of a 54 year old man from Chennai who is diabetic, and who also has Cushing Syndrome. He is a person with high risk for complications from COVID. He gave a swab for testing on Monday evening at KMC, Chennai.  (1/5)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost The trouble that they had in getting admitted helped me understand that at the root of the issue is a simple #lackofclearprotocol that every govt uses for admitting symptomatic COVID patients.   #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost Those within the govt healthcare system as well as providers working outside the system are experiencing this.  In the last week, I made two referrals of symptomatic COVID 19 positive patients who needed admission.  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost
@firstpost What I've said above is the long answer. The short answer is no. A lot more needs to be done from the Government’s end. (4/4)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost This is a matter of trust. This is also a matter of coordination between various care provisioning arms of the govt and the ability to communicate this back to the public in a timely manner. We are yet to see this coordination seamlessly. (3/4)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost

@firstpost in accessing clinical services especially when someone is showing symptoms. Citizens needs to trust the govt and its efforts, and the govt needs to understand that the concerns of the public are real and that field realities are not rosy. (2/4)  #DrAiswaryaExplains @firstpost
